# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1994-fifa-world-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] The **1930 FIFA World Cup final** was the final match of the 1930 World Cup, the inaugural edition of FIFA's competition for national football teams.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] The match was played at the Estadio Centenario in Montevideo, Uruguay, on 30 July 1930, and was contested by Uruguay and Argentina.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] The tournament comprised hosts Uruguay and 12 other teams that were invited by FIFA to compete.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] The 13 teams competed in a group stage, from which 4 teams qualified for the knockout stage.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] En route to the final, Uruguay finished first in Group 3, with two wins, after which they defeated Yugoslavia in the semi-final.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] Argentina finished first in Group 1 with three wins, before defeating the United States in the semi-final.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] The final took place in front of 93,000 supporters with the stadium gates opening at eight in the morning six hours before kick-off, and at noon the ground was full, and was refereed by John Langenus from Belgium.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] Before the match, a disagreement overshadowed the build-up to the match as which team would provide the match ball.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] FIFA intervened with a compromise, that Argentina would provide the ball for the first half, and Uruguay for the second.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] Uruguay opened the scoring in the 12th minute with Pablo Dorado opening the scoring.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] Carlos Peucelle equalised in the 20th minute, beating goalkeeper Enrique Ballestrero with a powerful shot.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] The tournament top scorer Guillermo Stábile gave Argentina a 2–1 lead going into the break.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] In the 57th minute, Uruguay leveled the score via a goal from Pedro Cea.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] Two more goals in the 68th and the 89th minute from Santos Iriarte and Héctor Castro put Uruguay up 4–2, sealing victory in the inaugural World Cup.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] Uruguay manager Alberto Suppici was 31 at the time, and still holds the record for being youngest coach of a FIFA World Cup winning team.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] Jules Rimet, president of FIFA, presented Uruguay with the World Cup Trophy, later to be named after him.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] The following day was declared a national holiday in Uruguay.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] In Buenos Aires, a mob threw stones at the Uruguayan consulate.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] The last living player from the final was Argentine striker Francisco Varallo, who died on 30 August 2010 aged 100.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] The last living Uruguayan from the final was Ernesto Mascheroni, who died on 3 July 1984 aged 76.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] Heading into the 1930 World Cup, Uruguay was experiencing its "golden generation" at the time.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] At continental level, Uruguay had won half of the South America Championship (forerunner to the Copa America), with the national team also winning the gold medal at the 1924 Summer Olympics in Paris and 1928 Summer Olympics in Amsterdam.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] For Argentina, they won the last two South American Championships in 1927 and 1929 and had also finished with a silver medal at the 1928 Olympics.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] Before the World Cup final, the two teams had played in one hundred and ten matches.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] This included eleven matches at the continental level, and two matches at the 1928 Olympic final, in which Uruguay won 2–1 in a replay.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] The last match before the World Cup between the two teams was at the 1930 Copa Newton which was only held two months prior on the 25 May in Buenos Aires which saw the match end in a 1–1 draw between the two teams but as Uruguay was the visiting country, they won the trophy.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] Uruguay was drawn in Group 3 with Peru and Romania.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] The opening match was against Peru at the Estadio Centenario was delayed by five days with the game being proceeded by a ceremony before the match.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] The first half saw the hosts intimidated by the 90,000 crowd as they would scrape for a one-nil victory with Héctor Castro scoring in the 65th minute to give Uruguay the win.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] At the end of the match, the Uruguayan press wanted a more demanding a more comprehensively attack in the next game against Romania.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] After 12 minutes, Pablo Dorado put the hosts into the lead, before Argentina winger Carlos Peucelle equalised 8 minutes later, beating goalkeeper Enrique Ballestrero with a powerful shot.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] In the 37th minute, tournament top scorer Guillermo Stábile gave Argentina a 2–1 lead going into the break.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] Uruguay leveled the score 12 minutes into the second half via a goal from Pedro Cea, and took the lead back for good with a Santos Iriarte goal in the 68th minute.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-final] With a minute remaining, Héctor Castro put Uruguay up 4–2, sealing victory in the inaugural World Cup.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-squads] Below are the **squads** for the **1930 FIFA World Cup** tournament in Uruguay.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup-squads] Yugoslavia (3 players from French clubs) and Peru (1 player from a Mexican club) were the only teams to have players from foreign clubs.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The **1930 FIFA World Cup** was the first FIFA World Cup, the world championship for men's national football teams.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] It took place in Uruguay from 13 to 30 July 1930.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] FIFA, football's international governing body, selected Uruguay as the host nation, as the country would be celebrating the centenary of its first constitution and the Uruguay national football team had retained their football title at the 1928 Summer Olympics.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] All matches were played in the Uruguayan capital, Montevideo, the majority at the purpose built Estadio Centenario.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Thirteen teams (seven from South America, four from Europe, and two from North America) entered the tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Only a handful of European teams chose to participate because of the difficulty of traveling to South America during the Great Depression.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The teams were divided into four groups, with the winner of each group progressing to the semifinals.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The first two World Cup matches took place simultaneously and were won by France and the United States, who defeated Mexico 4–1 and Belgium 3–0, respectively.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Lucien Laurent of France scored the first goal in World Cup history, while United States goalkeeper Jimmy Douglas posted the first clean sheet in the tournament the same day.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Argentina, Uruguay, the United States, and Yugoslavia won their respective groups to qualify for the semifinals.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] In the final, hosts and pre-tournament favourites Uruguay defeated Argentina 4–2 in front of 68,346 people to become the first nation to win the World Cup.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Francisco Varallo from Argentina was the last surviving player from this World Cup.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The 2030 FIFA World Cup opening match to be played at Estadio Centenario will honor the centennial anniversary of the World Cup.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The 1930 FIFA World Cup final is the first and only one to date to have been contested between two Spanish-speaking sides.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] It is also the only one that was contested between two South American nations, as the 1950 match between Brazil and Uruguay was technically the deciding match of the final group stage, not an actual cup final.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] FIFA, the governing body of world football, had been discussing the creation of a competition for national teams for several years prior to 1930.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The organisation had managed the football segment of the Summer Olympics on behalf of the International Olympic Committee since the early 20th century and the success of the competition at the 1924 and 1928 Olympic Games led to the formation of the FIFA World Cup.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] At the 17th FIFA congress, held in Amsterdam in May 1928, the competition was proposed by president Jules Rimet and accepted by the organisation's board, with vice-president Henri Delaunay proclaiming "international football can no longer be held within the confines of the Olympics".
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The first World Cup was the only one without qualification.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Every country affiliated with FIFA was invited to compete and given a deadline of 28 February 1930 to accept.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The competition was originally planned as a 16-team knockout tournament with a potential second division if enough teams entered; however, the number of teams failed to reach 16, so there were no qualifications.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Plenty of interest was shown by nations in the Americas; Argentina, Brazil, Bolivia, Chile, Mexico, Paraguay, Peru and the United States all entered.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] A total of seven South American teams participated, more than in any subsequent World Cup Finals.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] However, because of the long, costly trip by ship across the Atlantic Ocean and the length of absence required for players, very few European teams were inclined to take part as the effects of the Great Depression set in across the continent.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Some refused to countenance travel to South America in any circumstances, and no European entries were received before the February deadline.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] In an attempt to gain some European participation, the Uruguayan Football Association sent a letter of invitation to The Football Association, even though the British Home Nations (England, Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales) had resigned from FIFA at the time.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] This was rejected by the FA Committee on 18 November 1929.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Two months before the start of the tournament, no team from Europe had officially entered.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] FIFA president Rimet intervened and four European teams eventually made the trip by sea: Belgium, France, Romania and Yugoslavia.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The Romanians, managed by Constantin Rădulescu and coached by their captain Rudolf Wetzer and Octav Luchide, entered the competition following the intervention of the newly crowned King Carol II.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] He selected the squad personally and negotiated with employers to ensure that the players would still have jobs upon their return.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The French entered at the personal intervention of Rimet, but neither France's star defender Manuel Anatol nor the team's regular coach Gaston Barreau could be persuaded to make the trip.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The Belgians participated at the instigation of German-Belgian FIFA vice-president Rodolphe Seeldrayers.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The Romanians boarded the SS *Conte Verde* at Genoa, Italy; the French and Yugoslavs were picked up at Villefranche-sur-Mer, France, on 21 June 1930; and the Belgians embarked at Barcelona, Spain.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The *Conte Verde* carried Rimet, the trophy and the three designated European referees: Belgians John Langenus and Henri Christophe, along with Thomas Balvay, a Parisian who may have been English.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The Brazilian team were picked up when the boat docked in Rio de Janeiro on 29 June before arriving in Uruguay on 4 July.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The official ball used for the tournament was the T-Model.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The following 16 teams planned to compete at the final tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] However, only 13 teams participated because Egypt, Japan, and Siam withdrew.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Italy, Sweden, the Netherlands, Spain, Hungary, and Uruguay all lodged applications to host the event.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Uruguay's bid became the clear selection after all the other countries withdrew their bids.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Three stadiums were used: Estadio Centenario, Estadio Pocitos, and Estadio Gran Parque Central.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The Estadio Centenario was built both for the tournament and as a celebration of the centenary of Uruguayan independence.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Designed by Juan Scasso, it was the primary stadium for the tournament, referred to by Rimet as a "temple of football".
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] With a capacity of 90,000, it was the largest football stadium outside the British Isles.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The stadium hosted 10 of the 18 matches, including both semifinals and the final.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] However, the construction schedule was rushed and delayed by a rainy winter, therefore the Centenario was not ready for use until five days into the tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Early matches were played at smaller stadiums usually used by Montevideo football clubs Nacional and Peñarol, the 20,000 capacity Gran Parque Central and the Pocitos.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Fifteen referees participated in the tournament: four Europeans – two Belgians (Henri Christophe and John Langenus), a Frenchman (Thomas Balvay) and a Romanian (Constantin Rădulescu, also the Romanian team coach), and eleven from the Americas – among them six Uruguayans.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] To eliminate differences in the application of the Laws of the Game, the referees were invited to one short meeting to iron out the most conflicting issues that could arise.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] During the game, Saucedo, who was also the coach of Bolivia, awarded three penalties.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The following is the list of officials to serve as referees and linesmen.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Officials in italics were only employed as linesmen during the tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The thirteen teams were drawn into four groups, with Group 1 containing four teams and the others containing three.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Each group played a round-robin format, with the four group winners progressing to the knockout semifinal stage.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Uruguay, Argentina, Brazil, and the United States were seeded and kept apart in the draw, which took place in Montevideo once all the teams arrived.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] France's Lucien Laurent was the scorer of the first World Cup goal.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The first group was the only one to contain four teams: Argentina, Chile, France, and Mexico.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Two days after France's victory over Mexico, they faced group favourites Argentina.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Injuries hindered France; goalkeeper Alex Thépot had to leave the field after 20 minutes and Laurent, after a fierce tackle by Luis Monti, spent most of the match limping.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] However, they held out for most of the match, only succumbing to an 81st-minute goal scored from a Monti free kick.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The game featured an officiating controversy when referee Almeida Rêgo erroneously blew the final whistle six minutes early, with Frenchman Marcel Langiller clear on goal; play resumed only after protests from the French players.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Although France had played twice in 48 hours, Chile had yet to play their first match.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] They faced Mexico the following day, gaining a comfortable 3–0 win.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] France's final match, against Chile, featured the first penalty kick of the World Cup.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The first goalkeeper to save a penalty was Thépot of France on 19 July 1930, saving from Chile's Carlos Vidal in the 30th minute of the match.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] In Argentina's second match, against Mexico, three penalty kicks were awarded.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] During the same match on 19 July 1930, Mexico's Óscar Bonfiglio saved another penalty in the 23rd minute of the match against Argentina's Fernando Paternoster.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Guillermo Stábile scored a hat-trick in his international debut as Argentina won 6–3, despite the absence of their captain Manuel Ferreira, who had returned to Buenos Aires to take a law exam.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Qualification was decided by the group's final match, contested by Argentina and Chile, who had beaten France and Mexico, respectively.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The game was marred by a brawl sparked by a foul on Arturo Torres by Monti.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Argentina won 3–1 against their neighbours and advanced to the semifinals.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The second group contained Brazil, Bolivia, and Yugoslavia.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Brazil, the group seeds, were expected to progress, but in the group's opening match, unexpectedly lost 2–1 to Yugoslavia.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Going into the tournament Bolivia had never previously won an international match.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] For their opener they paid tribute to the hosts by wearing shirts each emblazoned with a single letter, spelling "Viva Uruguay" as the team lined up.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Both of Bolivia's matches followed a similar pattern, a promising start gradually transformed into heavy defeat.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Against Yugoslavia, they held out for an hour before conceding but were four goals down by the final whistle.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Misfortune played its part; several Bolivian goals were disallowed.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Against Brazil, when both teams had only pride to play for, the score was 1–0 to Brazil at half-time.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Brazil added three more in the second half, two of them scored by the multi-sportsman Preguinho.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Yugoslavia qualified for the semifinals.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Hosts Uruguay were in a group with Peru and Romania.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The opening match in this group saw the first player expulsion from the competition when Plácido Galindo of Peru was sent off against Romania.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The Romanians made their man advantage pay; their 3–1 win included two late goals and the fastest goal of the tournament; Adalbert Deșu opened the scoring after just 50 seconds.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] This match had the smallest crowd of any in World Cup history.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The official attendance was 2,459, but the actual figure is generally accepted to be around 300.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Construction delays at Estadio Centenario postponed Uruguay's first match to 18 July, the sixth match day of the tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The first to be held at the Centenario, it was preceded by a ceremony in honour of the Uruguayan centenary celebrations.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The Uruguayan team spent the four weeks preceding the match in a training camp, at which strict discipline was exercised.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Goalkeeper Andrés Mazali was dropped from the squad for breaking a curfew to visit his wife.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] One hundred years from the day of the creation of Uruguay's first constitution, the hosts won a tight match against Peru.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The result was viewed as a poor performance by the Uruguayan press.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Performance of the Peruvian goalkeeper Jorge Pardon drew particular praise from neutral observers.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Uruguay subsequently defeated Romania with ease, scoring four first-half goals to win 4–0.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The fourth group comprised Belgium, Paraguay, and the United States.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The American team, which contained a significant number of new caps, were reputedly nicknamed "the shot-putters" by an unnamed source in the French contingent.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] They beat their first opponent, Belgium, 3–0.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Both sides struggled early on in heavy rain and snowfall before the U.S. took control.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Belgian reports bemoaned the state of the pitch and refereeing decisions, claiming that the second goal was offside.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The group's second match, played in windy conditions, witnessed the first tournament hat-trick, scored by Bert Patenaude of the United States against Paraguay.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] With the United States having secured qualification, the final match in the group was a dead rubber.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The four group winners, Argentina, Yugoslavia, Uruguay and the United States, moved to the semifinals.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The two semifinal matches saw identical scores.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The first semifinal was played between the United States and Argentina on a rain-drenched pitch.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The United States team, which featured six British-born players, lost midfielder Raphael Tracey after 10 minutes to a broken leg as the match became violent.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] A Monti goal halfway through the first half gave Argentina a 1–0 half-time lead.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] In the second half, the strength of the United States team was overwhelmed by the pace of the Argentinian attacks, the match finishing 6–1 to Argentina.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] In the second semifinal, there were shades of the 1924 Summer Olympics match between Yugoslavia and Uruguay.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Here, though, Yugoslavia took a surprise lead through Đorđe Vujadinović.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Then shortly before half-time, Yugoslavia had a goal disallowed by a controversial offside decision.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The hosts scored three more in the second half to win 6–1, Pedro Cea completing a hat-trick.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The now-traditional match for third place was not established until 1934, so the format of the 1930 World Cup is unique in not distinguishing between the third and fourth-placed teams.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Occasional sources, notably a FIFA Bulletin from 1984, incorrectly imply that a match for third place occurred and was won 3–1 by Yugoslavia.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Accounts differ as to whether a match for third place was originally scheduled.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] According to a 2009 book by Hyder Jawad, Yugoslavia refused to play a match for third place because they were upset with the refereeing in their semifinal against Uruguay.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] At the end of the championship, the captains of the United States team (Tom Florie) and Yugoslavia (Milutin Ivković) both received bronze medals.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Yet a FIFA technical committee report on the 1986 World Cup included full retrospective rankings of all teams at all previous World Cup finals; this report ranked the United States third and Yugoslavia fourth, based on goal difference, a practice since continued by FIFA.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] According to this source, Yugoslavia was placed third because of the semifinal loss to the eventual champions, Uruguay.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The official recording however shows the United States team claiming third place.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The Yugoslavia team achieved the joint–biggest success in both Yugoslav and Serbian subsequent World Cup footballing history, by earning fourth place, a result that would be repeated in 1962.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Because of a dispute, a different ball was used in each half, one chosen by each team.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Argentina's ball (top) was used for the first half and Uruguay's ball (bottom) was used for the second half.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The resounding wins for Uruguay and Argentina in the semifinals meant the final was a repeat of the matchup in the 1928 Olympic final, which Uruguay had won 2–1 after a replay.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The final was played at the Estadio Centenario on 30 July.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Feelings ran high around the La Plata Basin as the Argentine supporters crossed the river with the war cry *Victoria o muerte* ("victory or death"), dispelling any uncertainty as to whether the tournament had captured the imagination of the public.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The ten boats earmarked to carry Argentine fans from Buenos Aires to Montevideo proved inadequate, and any number of assorted craft attempted the crossing.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] An estimated 10–15,000 Argentinians made the trip, but the port at Montevideo was so overwhelmed that many did not even make landfall before kick-off, let alone reach the stadium.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] At the stadium, supporters were searched for weapons.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The gates were opened at eight o'clock, six hours before kick-off, and by noon the ground was full, with an official attendance of 93,000.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] A disagreement overshadowed the build-up to the match as the teams failed to agree on who should provide the match ball, forcing FIFA to intervene and decree that the Argentine team would provide the ball for the first half and the Uruguayans would provide their own for the second.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Uruguay made one change from their semifinal line-up.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Monti played for Argentina despite receiving death threats on the eve of the match.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The hosts scored the opening goal through Pablo Dorado, a low shot from a position on the right.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Argentina, displaying superior passing ability, responded strongly.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Within eight minutes they were back on level terms; Carlos Peucelle received a Ferreira through-ball, beat his marker and equalised.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Shortly before half-time leading tournament goalscorer Guillermo Stábile gave Argentina a 2–1 lead.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Uruguay captain Nasazzi protested, maintaining that Stábile was offside but to no avail.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] In the second half Uruguay gradually became ascendant.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Shortly after Stábile missed a chance to score again, Uruguay attacked in numbers and Pedro Cea scored an equaliser.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Ten minutes later, a goal by Santos Iriarte gave Uruguay the lead, and just before full-time Castro made it 4–2 to seal the win.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Langenus ended the match a minute later and Uruguay added the title of World Cup winner to their mantle of Olympic champions.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Jules Rimet presented the World Cup Trophy, which was later named for him, to the head of the Uruguayan Football Association, Raúl Jude.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The following day was declared a national holiday in Uruguay; in the Argentinian capital, Buenos Aires, a mob threw stones at the Uruguayan consulate.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Francisco Varallo (who played as a forward for Argentina) was the last player in the final to die, on 30 August 2010.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] France, Yugoslavia and the United States all played friendlies in South America following the competition.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Brazil played France on 1 August, Yugoslavia on 10 August and the United States on 17 August, while Argentina hosted Yugoslavia on 3 August.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Uruguay's aggregate goal difference of +12 over four games, at an average of +3 per match, remains the highest average goal difference per match of any World Cup champion and the second-highest of any World Cup finals participant, after Hungary in 1954.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] There were 70 goals scored in 18 matches, for an average of 3.89 goals per match.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] There are several goals for which the statistical details are disputed.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] The goalscorers and timings used here are those of FIFA, the official record.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] Some other sources, such as RSSSF, state a different scorer, timing, or both.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1930-fifa-world-cup] In 1986, FIFA published a report that ranked all teams in each World Cup up to and including 1986, based on progress in the competition, overall results and quality of the opposition.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-final] The **1934 FIFA World Cup final** was the second edition of the football quadrennial tournament match contested by the men's national teams of FIFA to determine the 1934 FIFA World Cup champions: Italy and Czechoslovakia.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-final] It took place on 10 June 1934 at the Stadio Nazionale PNF in Rome, Italy.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-final] After going a goal down, Italy came back to win the match 2–1 despite temperatures approaching 40 °C (104 °F).
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-final] The last surviving player from that final was Czechoslovakia goalkeeper František Plánička who died on 20 July 1996 at the age of 92.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-final] Uruguay boycotted the 1934 edition due to the lack of European teams in the previous tournament and Argentina was eliminated in the first round of the tournament by Sweden, assured that a previous team would not be defending their title.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-final] This was the debut for each of the finalists in the FIFA World Cup.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-final] This was the eleventh contest between the two teams, their immediate previous match being at the 1933–35 Central European International Cup held in Florence, Italy; Italy prevailed 2–0.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-final] This leveled the head-to-head in the World Cup match to three all with four draws.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-final] Czechoslovakia took the lead with 19 minutes remaining through Antonín Puč.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-final] They held the lead for only 10 minutes as Italy drew level through striker Raimundo Orsi.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-final] Without any additional goals in regulation, the match was forced to go into the inaugural instance of a World Cup final extra time.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-final] Five minutes after the start of extra time, Italy took the lead with a goal from Angelo Schiavio; they held on for the victory.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-qualification] The **1934 FIFA World Cup** was the first World Cup for which teams had to qualify, after the finalists in the inaugural 1930 World Cup had participated by invitation from FIFA.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-qualification] With 32 teams having entered the 1934 competition, FIFA organized qualification rounds to select 16 teams for the finals.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-qualification] Even Italy, the host of the World Cup, had to earn its spot, the only time this has been the case.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-qualification] The previous champion Uruguay refused to defend its title because many European nations had declined to take part in the 1930 World Cup, held in Uruguay.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-qualification] The first match, between Sweden and Estonia, took place in Stockholm on 11 June 1933, with Swedish player Knut Kroon scoring the first goal.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-qualification] The last match was played in Rome only three days before the start of the tournament, as late entrant United States beat Mexico to become the final team to qualify.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-qualification] Estonia v Lithuania was not played since neither team could qualify with a win.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-qualification] Bulgaria withdrew, and the remaining matches were not played since Hungary and Austria were already assured of the top two spots.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-qualification] Germany v France was not played since both teams were already assured of the top two spots.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-qualification] Peru withdrew, so **Brazil** qualified automatically.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-qualification] Chile withdrew, so **Argentina** qualified automatically.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-qualification] The match to decide whether the United States or Mexico would qualify was played only three days before the start of the final tournament, as the United States submitted their entry too late.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-qualification] Thus, the match was played in Italy, so that the winner would effectively stay in the country for the tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-qualification] The Palestine football team consisted exclusively of Jewish and British players.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-qualification] FIFA states, in reference to the 1930s Palestine Mandate team, that the 'Palestine team' that participated in previous competitions in the 1930s was actually the forerunner of today's Israel team, and as such bears no relation to the modern-day Palestine national team.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-qualification] However, the region currently known as Palestine is considered one of the first Asian teams to compete in the FIFA World Cup qualifiers.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-qualification] Only six of the teams qualifying for the final competition – Argentina, Belgium, Brazil, France, Romania, and the USA – had already attended the World Cup in 1930.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-squads] The 1934 FIFA World Cup was an international football tournament that was held in Italy from 27 May to 10 June 1934.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-squads] Below are the squads the 16 national teams registered in the tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-squads] Brazil and Czechoslovakia were the only teams that had players from foreign clubs.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-squads] Rosters include reserves, alternates, and pre-selected players who may have participated in qualifiers and/or pre-tournament friendlies but not in the finals themselves.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-squads] Although registered to the official list, Raftl, Janda, Stroh, Kaburek, Walzhofer and Hassmann remained on standby in Austria.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-squads] Although registered to the official list, Bourgeois, Simons, Van Ingelgem, Ledent, Pappaert, Putmans, Versyp and Brichaut remained on standby in Belgium.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-squads] Although registered to the official list, Domingos, Tunga, Bile and Pamplona remained on standby in Brazil.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-squads] Although registered to the official list Daučík, Srbek, Šterc and Šimperský remained on standby in Czechoslovakia.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-squads] Although registered to the official list, Bakhati, El-Soury and Youssef remained on standby in Egypt.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-squads] Although registered to the official list, Défossé, Vandooren, Beaucourt, Delmer, Korb, Laurent and Courtois remained on standby in France.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-squads] Although registered to the official list, Buchloh, Albrecht, Dienert and Streb remained on standby in Germany.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-squads] Although registered to the official list, Vrauwdeunt and Paauwe remained on standby in the Netherlands.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-squads] The Romanian Football Federation had nominated Zoltán Beke in case Bindea did not recover in time from injury, but this contravened FIFA regulations and so Beke, who travelled with the team to Italy, was not eligible to play.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-squads] Although registered to the official list, Konrard, Bürger, Juhász, Weichelt, Baratky, Klimek and Schwartz remained on standby in Romania.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-squads] Although registered to the official list, Hilario and Sabater remained on standby in Spain.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-squads] Although registered to the official list, Hult, Jansson, Bunke, Holmberg and Lundhal remained on standby in Sweden.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup-squads] Although registered to the official list, Huber, Gobet, Loichot and Hochsträsser remained on standby in Switzerland.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The **1934 FIFA World Cup** was the 2nd edition of the FIFA World Cup, the quadrennial international football championship for senior men's national teams.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] It took place in Italy from 27 May to 10 June 1934.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The 1934 World Cup was the first in which teams had to qualify to take part.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Thirty-two nations entered the competition; sixteen teams qualified for the final tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Reigning champions Uruguay boycotted the tournament as only four European teams had accepted their invitation to the 1930 tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Italy beat Czechoslovakia 2–1 to become the second World Cup champions and the first European winners.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The 1934 World Cup was marred by being a high-profile instance of a sporting event being used for overt political gain.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] In particular, Benito Mussolini was keen to use this World Cup as a means of promoting fascism.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The Federale 102 ball, which was manufactured in Italy, was the match ball provided for the 1934 World Cup.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] After a lengthy decision-making process in which FIFA's executive committee met eight times, Italy was chosen as the host nation at a meeting in Stockholm on 9 October 1932.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The decision was taken by the executive committee without a ballot of members.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The Italian bid was chosen in preference to one from Sweden; the Italian government assigned a budget of Lire 3.5 million to the tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] For the first time, teams had to play qualifying matches to enter the competition: 32 countries applied to enter the finals tournament, of which 16 qualified.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Even so, there were several notable absentees.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Reigning World Cup holders Uruguay declined to participate, in protest at the refusal of several European countries to travel to South America for the previous World Cup, which Uruguay had hosted in 1930.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] As a result, the 1934 World Cup is the only one in which the reigning champions did not participate.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The British Home Nations, in a period of self-imposed exile from FIFA, also refused to participate, even though FIFA had offered England and Scotland direct entry to the tournament without qualification.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Despite their role as hosts, Italy were still required to qualify, the only time the host needed to do so.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The qualifying matches were arranged on a geographical basis.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Withdrawals by Chile and Peru meant that Argentina and Brazil qualified without playing a single match.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Twelve of the sixteen places were allocated to Europe, three to the Americas, and one to Africa or Asia (including Turkey).
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Only 10 of the 32 entrants, and 4 of the 16 qualified teams (Brazil, Argentina, United States, and Egypt, the first African team to qualify for a World Cup finals tournament), were from outside Europe.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The last place in the finals was contested between the United States and Mexico only three days before the start of the tournament in a one-off match in Rome, which the United States won.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The following 16 teams qualified for the final tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Ten of these teams made their first World Cup appearance.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] This included 9 of the 12 European teams (Italy, Germany, Spain, the Netherlands, Hungary, Czechoslovakia, Sweden, Austria, and Switzerland) as well as Egypt.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Egypt was the first team from Africa in the finals and did not qualify again until the next time the competition was held in Italy, in 1990.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The number of supporters travelling from other countries was higher than at any previous football tournament, including 7,000 from the Netherlands and 10,000 each from Austria and Switzerland.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The group stage used in the first World Cup was discarded in favour of a straight knockout tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] If a match was tied after ninety minutes, then thirty minutes of extra time were played.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] If the score was still tied after extra time, the match was replayed the next day.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The eight seeded teams – Argentina, Brazil, Germany, Italy, the Netherlands, Austria, Czechoslovakia and Hungary – were kept apart in the first round.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] All eight first-round matches kicked off at the same time.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Hosts and favourites Italy won handsomely, defeating the USA 7–1; *The New York Times* correspondent wrote that "only the fine goal-tending of Julius Hjulian of Chicago kept the score as low as it was".
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Internal disputes meant Argentina's squad for the tournament did not contain a single member of the team which had reached the final in 1930.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] In the end, *La Albiceleste* would partake with an amateur squad.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Against Sweden in Bologna, Argentina twice took the lead, but two goals by Sven Jonasson and a winner by Knut Kroon gave Sweden a 3–2 victory.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Fellow South Americans Brazil also suffered an early exit.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Spain beat them comfortably, with 3–1 as the final score.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] For the only time in World Cup history, the last eight consisted entirely of European teams – Austria, Czechoslovakia, Germany, Hungary, Italy, Spain, Sweden, and Switzerland.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] All four non-European teams who made the journey to Italy were eliminated after one match.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] In the quarterfinals, the first replayed match in World Cup history took place, when Italy and Spain drew 1–1 after extra time.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Italy won the replay 1–0; their play so physical that at least three Spaniards had to depart the field with injuries.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Italy then went on to beat Austria in the semifinals by the same score.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Meanwhile, Czechoslovakia secured their place in the final by beating Germany 3–1.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The Stadium of the National Fascist Party was the venue for the final.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] With 80 minutes played, the Czechoslovaks led 1–0.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The Italians managed to score before the final whistle and then added another goal in extra time to be crowned World Cup winners.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Over the years, several sources have reported that the tournament was marred by bribery and corruption and could have been influenced by Italian dictator Benito Mussolini, who used it as a propaganda tool for fascism.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] According to these accusations, Mussolini personally selected referees for the matches where the Italy national team were playing, while the Italian government meddled in FIFA's organisation of events, reorganising the logistics of the matches to further promote fascism.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Later commentary has described Italy's successful defence of the following World Cup in France in 1938 as an opportunity to counter the allegations surrounding the 1934 tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] For a list of all squads that appeared in the final tournament, see *1934 FIFA World Cup squads*.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] With five goals, Oldřich Nejedlý was the top scorer in the tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] In total, 70 goals were scored by 45 players, with none of them credited as an own goal.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] In 1986, FIFA published a report that ranked all teams in each World Cup up to and including 1986, based on progress in the competition, overall results and quality of the opposition (not counting replay results).
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The **1994 FIFA World Cup** was the 15th FIFA World Cup, the world championship for men's national soccer teams.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] It was hosted by the United States and took place from June 17 to July 17, 1994, at nine venues across the country.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The United States was chosen as the host by FIFA on July 4, 1988.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Despite soccer's relative lack of popularity in the host nation, the tournament was the most financially successful in World Cup history.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Brazil won the competition, defeating Italy in the final at the Rose Bowl in Pasadena, California.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The game ended 0–0 after extra time, and Brazil won 3–2 in a penalty shootout.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] It was the first World Cup final to be decided on penalties.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The victory made Brazil the first nation to win four World Cup titles.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] There were three new entrants in the tournament: Greece, Nigeria, and Saudi Arabia; Russia also appeared as a separate nation for the first time, following the breakup of the Soviet Union, and for the first time since 1938, a unified Germany took part in the tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] It was also the defending champion, but was eliminated in the quarterfinals by Bulgaria.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] It was the first World Cup in which three points were awarded for a win instead of two and also the first with the back-pass rule.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] This was done to encourage a more attacking style of play as a response to the criticism of the defensive tactics and low-scoring matches of the 1990 World Cup.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] This resulted in an average of 2.71 goals per match, compared to 2.21 in 1990.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Three nations bid to host the event: United States, Brazil, and Morocco.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The vote was held in Zurich on July 4, 1988 (Independence Day in the United States), and only took one round with the United States bid receiving a little over half of the votes by the FIFA Executive Committee members.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] FIFA hoped that by staging the world's most prestigious tournament there, it would lead to a growth of interest in the sport.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] An inspection committee also found that the proposed Brazilian stadiums were deficient, while the Moroccan bid relied on the construction of nine new stadiums.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Conversely, all the proposed stadiums in the United States were already built and fully functioning; U.S.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Soccer spent $500 million preparing and organizing the tournament, far less than the billions other countries previously had spent and subsequently would spend on preparing for this tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The U.S. bid was seen as the favorite and was prepared in response to losing the right to be the replacement host for the 1986 tournament following Colombia's withdrawal.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] One condition FIFA imposed was the creation of a professional soccer league – Major League Soccer was founded in 1993 and began operating in 1996.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] There was some initial controversy about awarding the World Cup to a country where soccer was not a nationally popular sport, and at the time, in 1988, the U.S. no longer had a professional league; the North American Soccer League, established in 1967, had folded in 1984 after attendance faded.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The success of the 1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles, particularly the soccer tournament that drew 1.4 million spectators throughout the event, also contributed to FIFA's decision.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The United States had previously bid to host the 1986 FIFA World Cup, after Colombia withdrew as the host nation in November 1982 because of economic concerns.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Despite a presentation led by former North American Soccer League players Pelé and Franz Beckenbauer, as well as former United States Secretary of State Henry Kissinger, the executive committee selected Mexico.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] There were proposals by FIFA to introduce larger goals and breaks after every quarter instead of just at halftime in order to appease U.S. television advertisers.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] These proposals were met with resistance, and ultimately rejected.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The games were played in nine cities across the contiguous United States.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] All stadiums had a capacity of at least 53,000 and were occupied by professional or college American football teams.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Other host city candidates included Atlanta, Denver, Kansas City, Las Vegas, Miami, Minneapolis, New Orleans, Philadelphia, Seattle, and Tampa, as well as smaller communities such as Annapolis, Maryland; Columbus, Ohio; Corvallis, Oregon; and New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Some sites, including Joe Robbie Stadium in Miami and Candlestick Park in San Francisco, were rejected because of conflicts with Major League Baseball.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Stanford Stadium in the San Francisco Bay Area's South Bay and the Citrus Bowl in Orlando, Florida, were picked instead (the Miami Orange Bowl, another Miami venue, required major renovations to meet tournament standards).
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Rose Bowl hosted the most matches with eight, four of them in the knockout stage, including the final.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Giants Stadium hosted seven games including a semifinal; Foxborough Stadium, Stanford Stadium, and the Cotton Bowl hosted six games each, and Soldier Field, Robert F.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Kennedy Memorial Stadium, and the Citrus Bowl hosted five games each.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Pontiac Silverdome, the first indoor stadium used in a World Cup, hosted four group-stage games, the fewest of any venue; it was also the only one of the nine used that did not host knockout-round games.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Four teams—one African, one Asian, and two European—made their debuts at the 1994 tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Nigeria qualified from the African zone alongside Cameroon and Morocco as CAF was granted three spots as a result of the strong performances by African teams in 1986 and 1990.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the Asian zone, Saudi Arabia qualified for the first time by topping the final round group ahead of South Korea as both edged out Japan, which was close to making its own World Cup debut, but was denied by Iraq in what became known as the "Agony of Doha".
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the European zone, Greece made its first World Cup appearance after topping a group from which Russia also qualified, competing for the first time following the dissolution of the Soviet Union.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The defending champion, West Germany, had reunited with East Germany, so a united Germany took part for the first time since the 1938 World Cup.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Norway qualified for the first time since 1938, Bolivia for the first time since 1950 (and the last time as of 2026), and Switzerland for the first time since 1966.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Norway's 56-year gap between appearances in the tournament equaled Egypt's record from the previous tournament as the longest.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Mexico qualified for the first time since 1978.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] England was notably absent; after finishing in fourth place in 1990, it failed to qualify for the 1994 event, finishing third in its qualifying group.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] This was England's first failure to qualify for a World Cup since 1978.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] It was also the first time that none of the home nations (England, Northern Ireland, Scotland, and Wales) qualified since first entering in 1950.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Following its failure to qualify for the 1990 tournament, France again missed the 1994 edition after conceding a goal in the final minute of its concluding qualifying match against Bulgaria.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The resulting defeat left France third in the group, behind both Bulgaria and Sweden.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The qualification campaigns of Czechoslovakia and Yugoslavia were affected by political events.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The nation of Czechoslovakia dissolved in 1993, completing its qualifying group under the name "Representation of Czechs and Slovaks" (RCS), but failed to qualify for the finals, having been edged out by Romania and Belgium in Group 4.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Yugoslavia (which was supposed to play in Group 5) was suspended from international competition in 1992 as part of United Nations sanctions against the country as a result of the Yugoslav Wars.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The sanctions were not lifted until 1994, by which time it was no longer possible for the team to qualify.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Chile's suspension from the 1990 World Cup, following the forced interruption of its qualification game against Brazil, extended to the 1994 qualifiers as well.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The following 24 teams qualified for the tournamentː Their pre-tournament FIFA World Ranking from June 1994 is shown in parentheses.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Teams were selected following usual FIFA rules with 22 players.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Greece, Italy, Saudi Arabia, and Spain were the only countries that had all their players coming from domestic teams, while the Republic of Ireland and Nigeria had no players from domestic teams.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Saudi Arabia was the only team with no players from European teams.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The FIFA Organizing Committee upheld the tradition to seed the host (United States) and defending champion (Germany), along with the other four teams ranked in the top five based on their results obtained in the last three FIFA World Cups.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The newly introduced FIFA World Ranking was not used as part of the calculated ranking for the seeding in this World Cup, as FIFA considered it to be too new.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Despite that it was not used in any way, for comparison purposes the teams' pre-tournament FIFA World ranking position from June 1994 are shown in parentheses, followed by the official and used ranking (OR) position determined by the results obtained in the last three world cups.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The six top-seeded teams, were allocated in pot 1 and would be drawn into the first position of the six groups playing in the group stage.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The remaining 18 teams were allocated into three pots based on geographical sections, with the: six qualified teams from Africa and Americas in pot 2, the top-6 ranked European teams in pot 3, while pot 4 comprised the 7th-10th best qualified European teams along with the two qualified Asian teams.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] United States and Mexico could not be drawn in the same group, because only one CONCACAF team per group.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Brazil and Argentina could not be drawn with another South American team, because only one CONMEBOL team per group.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The draw took place at the Las Vegas Convention Center and was televised live on December 19, 1993, on ESPN in the United States and Eurosport in all Europe with English language commentary on the latter channel by Scottish sportscaster Archie Macpherson.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The draw presenters were Dick Clark and Faye Dunaway.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The three other top-seeded teams would be located at the first position of either group B/D/F, with the decision largely depending on the identity of the other drawn group members for the seeded teams.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Therefore, this last decision would only be made by a secret vote made by the FIFA Organizing Committee a few minutes after all teams had been drawn for all groups, and the decision would only be announced as the last step of the televised draw event.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] To make this procedure possible, the six drawn groups would during the draw be given the colors green, orange, white, black, pink and blue; and the closing remarks at the event would then reveal the group letters represented by the colors.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Pot 3 was used to draw one European team to each of the six colored groups, with the draw conducted in the color order from left to right (green, orange, white, black, pink, blue).
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Pot 4 was used to draw one European/Asian team to each of six colored groups, with the draw conducted in the color order from left to right (green, orange, white, black, pink, blue).
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The exact group position number for the teams (2, 3 or 4) in each colored group, were also drawn immediately from six special group bowls, after each respective team had been drawn from pot 2, 3 and 4.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Group letters behind each color (green, orange, white, black, pink and blue) would finally be decided by a final secret FIFA Organizing Committee vote, being announced as the last part of the televised event.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The draw was officiated by FIFA general-secretary Joseph Blatter.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Numbers for placement in the group were drawn by German legend Franz Beckenbauer, heavyweight boxing champion Evander Holyfield, and comedian and actor Robin Williams.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] In each group, the teams played three games, one against each of the other teams.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] After completion of the group stage, the best two teams in each group, as well as the four best-ranked third-place teams, advanced to the round of 16 in the knockout stage.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] This format was identical to the tournament structure used in 1986 and 1990 except that a win now earned three points instead of two, to encourage more attacking play.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The format of the competition stayed the same as in the 1990 World Cup: 24 teams qualified, divided into six groups of four.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Sixteen teams would qualify for the knockout phase: the six group winners, the six group runners-up, and the four third-placed teams with the best records.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] This was the last time this format was used, due to the expansion of the finals tournament in 1998 to 32 teams.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] FIFA introduced three rule changes for this tournament to encourage attacking play: three points awarded for a win in a group stage match instead of two, a relaxed offside rule and a ban on picking up back-passes to goalkeepers.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The number of goals increased to 2.73 per game from the record-low of 2.21 in 1990.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cities with the most consistently difficult conditions were Orlando and Dallas in the South, because of the combination of heat and extreme humidity, while Detroit proved to be difficult due to the Pontiac Silverdome being an air-supported stadium.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The tournament saw the end of Diego Maradona's World Cup career, having played in the 1982, 1986, and 1990 World Cups, and leading Argentina to the 1986 World Cup title and the final of the 1990 World Cup.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Maradona was expelled from the tournament by FIFA after he failed a drug test that uncovered ephedrine, a weight-loss drug, in his blood.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Colombia, despite high expectations due to their style and impressive qualifying campaign, failed to advance from the round robin.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The team was dogged by influence from betting syndicates and drug cartels, with coach Francisco Maturana receiving death threats over squad selection.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] After scoring an own goal for the United States and effectively eliminating Colombia from the competition, defender Andrés Escobar was shot to death on his return to Colombia outside a bar in a Medellín suburb 10 days later, possibly in retaliation for his mistake.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Bulgaria was one of the biggest surprises of the tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Bulgarians had never won a game in five previous World Cup appearances, but, led by Hristo Stoichkov, who would eventually share the tournament lead in scoring, they presented a formidable challenge for the title.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The team won two of their three group games to qualify for the second round, where they advanced after a 3–1 penalty shootout win over Mexico.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] They then faced reigning world champions Germany in the quarterfinals, where goals from Stoichkov and Letchkov gave them a 2–1 victory.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Bulgaria went on to finish in fourth place after losing to Italy in the semifinals and Sweden in the match for third place.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The host nation United States, after a 23rd-place finish in the 1990 tournament, advanced to the second round as one of the best third-place teams.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] They were eliminated in the Round of 16 in a 1–0 defeat to Brazil on Independence Day.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Brazil's win over the hosts helped take them to the final against Italy.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Brazil's path was relatively smooth as they never trailed over 270 minutes of the knockout stage, defeating the Netherlands in the quarterfinals and Sweden in the semis after the aforementioned win over the hosts.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Italians meanwhile had made hard work of reaching the final.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] During the group stage, Italy struggled and narrowly advanced to the next round, despite losing 1–0 to the Republic of Ireland.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Italian playmaker Roberto Baggio, who as the reigning FIFA World Player of the Year and Ballon D'Or holder, was expected to be one of the stars of the tournament, had not yet scored a goal.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] During the Round of 16 games against Nigeria, Italy was trailing 1–0 in the dying minutes when Baggio scored the tying goal, forcing the game into extra time.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] He scored again with a penalty kick to send Italy through.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Baggio carried the Italians from there, scoring the game-winning goal in the quarterfinal against Spain, and both goals in Italy's semifinal victory over Bulgaria.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The match for third place was set between Bulgaria and Sweden, the team which scored more goals than any other in this World Cup with 15 over seven matches.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] These teams had also previously met in the qualifying group.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Swedish forward Tomas Brolin was named to the All-star team, alongside Bulgaria's Krasimir Balakov and Hristo Stoichkov.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The 1994 FIFA World Cup was the last edition of the tournament in which bronze medals were also awarded to the team finishing fourth after losing the third-place play-off.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Consequently, Bulgaria became the last fourth-placed team to receive bronze medals at a FIFA World Cup.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The final game at the Rose Bowl was tense but devoid of scoring chances.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] It was the second time in 24 years that the two nations had met in a final.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] After 120 goalless minutes, the World Cup was decided for the first time by a penalty shootout.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] After four rounds, Brazil led 3–2, and Baggio, playing injured, had to score to keep Italy's hopes alive.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] He missed by shooting it over the crossbar, and the Brazilians were crowned champions for the fourth time.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] After the game ended, Vice President Al Gore hosted the awarding ceremony by handing Brazilian captain Dunga the prestigious trophy; the Brazil national team dedicated the title to the deceased Formula One motor racing champion and countryman Ayrton Senna, who had died two and a half months prior.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The tournament's Golden Boot went jointly to Bulgaria's Stoichkov and Oleg Salenko of Russia, the latter becoming the first player to score five goals in a game, coming in a 6–1 victory against Cameroon.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Both players scored six goals in the tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Brazilian striker Romário, with five goals, won the Golden Ball as the tournament's best player.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] To this day, the total attendance for the final tournament of nearly 3.6 million remains the highest in World Cup history, despite the expansion of the competition from 24 to 32 teams at the 1998 World Cup in France.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The opening ceremony of the World Cup was held on June 17 at Chicago's Soldier Field.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The ceremony was emceed by Oprah Winfrey, who introduced Diana Ross: she gave a musical performance.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Ross was also intended to score a penalty at the beginning of her performance, with the goal then splitting in two as part of a pre-orchestrated stunt.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Instead, she kicked the ball wide to the left, missing the goal, but the goalposts collapsed anyway in accordance with the stunt plans.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] In addition, Daryl Hall and Jon Secada also gave musical performances.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] It was officially opened by then-President Bill Clinton.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Group A game between the United States and Switzerland was the first to take place indoors, played under the roof at the Pontiac Silverdome.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Following the tournament, Colombian defender Andrés Escobar was shot dead on his return to Colombia, possibly in retaliation, after his own goal had contributed to his country's elimination.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Victories against Colombia and the United States (in front of a crowd of 93,869) were enough to see Romania through as group winners, despite a 4–1 hammering by Switzerland in between.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The magnitude of that victory allowed Switzerland to move ahead of the United States on goal difference, although the hosts qualified for the second round as one of the best third-placed teams.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Switzerland's 4–1 victory over Romania came nearly 40 years to the date of Switzerland's last World Cup victory, also a 4–1 victory, on that occasion over Italy.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The United States' 2–1 victory over Colombia was its first World Cup victory since their 1–0 upset over England in the 1950 World Cup.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Group B produced two of the four semifinalists of this World Cup — Brazil and Sweden — and was also one of the two groups in which only two, rather than three, sides progressed to the second round.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The match between the two eliminated teams, Cameroon and Russia, broke two World Cup records.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Oleg Salenko of Russia remains the only player to score five goals in a single World Cup game as Russia won 6–1.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The goals also ensured that Salenko finished the tournament joint-top scorer with six goals, having previously bagged one against Sweden.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cameroon left a mark too as Roger Milla, at the age of 42, became the oldest World Cup goalscorer of all time, as he grabbed his side's consolation goal in the game.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The result was not enough to take Russia through following losses to Brazil and Sweden.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Brazil beat Cameroon, and then confirmed the top spot with a draw to Sweden.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Swedes also progressed, finishing in second place with five points.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Sweden's 3–1 victory over Russia was the nation's first World Cup victory since July 3, 1974.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Russia failed to progress to the second round for the second time (accounting for the Soviet Union's results four years before), while Cameroon failed to repeat their surprise performance from the previous tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] As was the case with Group B, Group C would only send two teams into the Round of 16 as Spain and defending champions Germany progressed to round two.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Coming from two goals down with four minutes left to snatch a 2–2 draw against Spain, the South Koreans very nearly eclipsed that feat against Germany when they came from 3–0 down to lose narrowly 3–2.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] In spite of these comebacks, South Korea was held to a 0–0 draw against Bolivia in their other group game when a win would have seen them through.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Spain's late implosion against the South Koreans effectively decided that it would be Germany who won the group and not them.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Germany, who defeated Bolivia 1–0 in the tournament's opening game, finished with seven points.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Spain had to settle for second place despite leading in all three games.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Despite Bolivia finishing last in the group, Erwin Sanchez made team history after scoring the nation's first World Cup goal in a 3–1 loss to Spain.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Prior to 1994, Bolivia had never scored in either of their previous appearances at the 1930 and 1950 World Cups.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Maradona only played with Argentina during their first two games, both in Foxborough (playing Greece and Nigeria and scoring his last ever World Cup goal against the former); he was thrown out of the tournament after testing positive for ephedrine.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Having qualified for the tournament through a last-gasp goal against France, Bulgaria surprised many people, as the nation had never even won a game at the World Cup finals prior to this tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Despite losing its opening game 3–0 to Nigeria, Bulgaria came back in style with a 4–0 win over neighbor Greece (who had suffered exactly the same fate five days earlier against Argentina), and a 2–0 win against Argentina saw them advance.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Argentina had actually been winning the group going into injury time, while Bulgaria played the last 25 minutes with 10 men; however, a 91st-minute header from Nasko Sirakov meant that Argentina dropped two places and finished third.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Nigeria won the group on goal difference.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Bulgaria's victory over Argentina earned them second place.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Group E remains the only group in World Cup history in which all four teams finished with the same points.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] All four teams even had the same goal difference.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] It began at Giants Stadium where Ray Houghton's chip ensured a shock Irish victory over the then-three-time champions Italy by 1–0, as well as gaining a measure of revenge for the previous World Cup, in which Italy both hosted and eliminated Ireland at the quarterfinal stage.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The next day in Washington, Norway played its first World Cup game since 1938 and Kjetil Rekdal's goal five minutes from time proved decisive in an equally tense encounter as Norway beat Mexico.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the second round of group play, Luis García's double had Mexico 2–0 up and in control of the game before a disagreement on the touchline resulted in fines for both Republic of Ireland's manager, Jack Charlton, and their striker John Aldridge.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Aldridge was able to regain concentration in time to score six minutes from the end of the game to make it 2–1.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Despite their loss, Aldridge's goal proved crucial to Ireland in the final group standings.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] During the previous day at Giants Stadium in New Jersey, Italy's World Cup hopes seemed to be diminishing fast as goalkeeper Gianluca Pagliuca was sent off with the game still at 0–0.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Yet despite this, Italy was still able to salvage an important 1–0 victory.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Norway would ultimately pay a price for their inability to take advantage of Pagliuca's dismissal.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the final group game, the Republic of Ireland qualified after a dreary 0–0 draw with Norway; while Massaro and Bernal traded strikes as Italy and Mexico played to a 1–1 draw.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Those results meant that Mexico won the group on goals scored, with three in the group.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] With Ireland and Italy also progressing having finished with identical records, the Irish team qualified as second place as a result of their victory against the Italians.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Despite having only conceded one goal, Norway exited the tournament on goals scored; their solo goal against Mexico proving inadequate to qualify for the round of 16.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Just as happened to Argentina in Group D, Belgium endured the same fate in Group F.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Despite winning both of its first two matches 1–0 against Morocco and neighbors Netherlands, Belgium finished third as, in an upset, it lost to tournament newcomers Saudi Arabia 1–0 in the third game.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] During that game, Saudi player Saaed Al-Owairan ran from his own half through a maze of Belgian players to score the game's only goal.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Saudi Arabia advanced through to the Round of 16 as well, having also defeated Morocco 2–1.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Netherlands endured a somewhat nervier experience.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] The opening 2–1 victory against Saudi Arabia was followed by the 1–0 loss against Belgium before another 2–1 victory against Morocco, with Bryan Roy scoring the winner a mere 12 minutes from time, saw the Dutch win the group having scored more goals than Belgium and beaten Saudi Arabia.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p01] Morocco, despite losing all three of their group games, did not leave without a fight, as each of their losses were by just a single goal, 1–0 to Belgium, 2–1 to Saudi Arabia, and 2–1 to the Netherlands.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p02] Hristo Stoichkov and Oleg Salenko received the Golden Boot for scoring six goals.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p02] In total, 141 goals were scored by 81 players, with only one of them credited as an own goal.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p02] The All-star team is a squad consisting of the eleven most impressive players at the 1994 World Cup, as selected by FIFA's Technical Study Group.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p02] After the tournament, FIFA published a ranking of all teams that competed in the 1994 World Cup finals based on progress in the competition, overall results and quality of the opposition.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p02] The sponsors of the 1994 FIFA World Cup were divided into two categories: FIFA World Cup Sponsors and USA Supporters.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p02] The former were major FIFA sponsors, while the latter joined for the 1994 tournament.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p02] The official mascot of this World Cup was "Striker, the World Cup Pup", a dog wearing a red, white and blue soccer uniform with a ball.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p02] Striker was designed by the Warner Bros. animation team.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p02] A dog was picked as the mascot because dogs are a popular domestic pet in the United States.
[src:1994-fifa-world-cup/1994-fifa-world-cup-p02] The official match ball was "Questra", manufactured by Adidas.
